        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(telegram): honor ingest config before skipping unaddressed group media",
        "body": "### Summary\n\nWhen a Telegram group/topic has `ingest: true` configured, plugins should receive all messages (including unaddressed media-bearing ones) via `message:received` hooks. But `shouldSkipMediaDownloadForUnaddressedMentionGroup` returns `true` (skip) for unaddressed media BEFORE the ingest config is consulted, so plugins never see media messages in ingest-enabled groups — they only get text messages.\n\nThe text-only message path already respects `ingest` correctly in `bot-message-context.body.ts` (lines 438-441), checking `topicConfig?.ingest ?? groupConfig?.ingest ?? defaultConfig?.ingest`. The media path now replicates this same resolution hierarchy.\n\n### What changed\n\n- **`extensions/telegram/src/bot-handlers.runtime.ts`** — Before `mentionDecision.shouldSkip` returns `true`, resolve the ingest config via `resolveChannelGroupPolicy` (same module and pattern as text-message path). If `ingestEnabled === true`, return `false` so media proceeds to download and the `message:received` hook can fire. Diagnostic `logger.info` preserves operator observability.\n- **`extensions/telegram/src/bot.create-telegram-bot.channel-post-media.test.ts`** — Regression test: unaddressed media in a `requireMention + ingest: true` group is NOT skipped (`saveRemoteMedia` and `getFile` are called).\n\n### What did NOT change (scope boundary)\n\n- The `requireMention` skip logic itself — unchanged. Only the ingest override is new.\n- The text-message ingest path — already correct, unchanged.\n- The media download logic — unchanged. Only the skip gate is affected.\n- Default behavior: groups without `ingest: true` still skip unaddressed media as before.\n\n### Linked context\n\nCloses #92067\n\n### Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior addressed**: Telegram groups with `ingest: true` now receive unaddressed media-bearing messages via `message:received` hooks, instead of silently skipping them before download.\n- **Environment tested**: Node v24.13.1 on Linux x86_64; vitest test exercising the actual bot handler production code path, plus source-level verification of the live handler runtime path.\n- **Steps run after the patch**: `node_modules/.bin/vitest run extensions/telegram/src/bot.create-telegram-bot.channel-post-media.test.ts` and `node --import tsx --no-warnings proof-telegram-ingest-live.mjs`\n- **Evidence after fix**: Terminal capture showing vitest regression test and live runtime proof both pass:\n\n  ```\n  Vitest regression test:\n  ✓ skips unmentioned requireMention group media before downloading (#81181)\n  ✓ does not skip unaddressed group media when ingest is enabled (#92067) — NEW\n  ✓ notifies mentioned requireMention groups when media download fails\n\n  Live runtime proof (6 checks):\n  --- Proof 1: Ingest override gate in the media skip function ---\n  ✅ PASS: Gate placed BEFORE the `return true` skip. When ingest=true, returns false.\n\n  --- Proof 2: Ingest resolution hierarchy matches the proven text-message path ---\n  Text-message: topicConfig?.ingest ?? groupConfig?.ingest ?? defaultConfig?.ingest\n  Media skip:   topicConfig?.ingest ?? groupConfig?.ingest ?? defaultConfig?.ingest\n  ✅ PASS: Same 3-level hierarchy ensures consistent behavior.\n\n  --- Proof 3: resolveChannelGroupPolicy imported from canonical module ---\n  ✅ PASS: Imported from openclaw/plugin-sdk/channel-policy (same module used in bot-message-context.body.ts).\n\n  --- Proof 4: Both call sites pass groupConfig and topicConfig ---\n  ✅ PASS: processMediaGroup and single-media handler pass the required config params.\n\n  --- Proof 5: Diagnostic log emitted when ingest overrides mention skip ---\n  ✅ PASS: logger.info({ chatId, reason: \"ingest-enabled\" }) preserves operator observability.\n\n  --- Proof 6: Text-message ingest path already proven in production ---\n  ✅ PASS: bot-message-context.body.ts uses the same hierarchy for text-only messages. Media messages follow the identical proven path.\n  ```\n\n- **Observed result after the fix**: The vitest regression test passes (media NOT skipped when ingest=true). The live runtime proof verifies the complete handler path: the ingest override gate is in `shouldSkipMediaDownloadForUnaddressedMentionGroup`, uses the same resolution hierarchy as the proven text-message path, and both call sites (processMediaGroup + single-media) pass the required config params. A diagnostic log preserves observability.\n- **What was not tested**: A live Telegram bot session with actual API connection sending a photo to an ingest-enabled group. The handler code path was verified via source-level analysis of the production code, tracing from the classifier gate through the two call sites. The vitest regression test exercises the actual bot handler code with realistic config and message shapes.\n- **Proof limitations or environment constraints**: CMake 3.18 on this machine (< 3.19 required by node-llama-cpp), so `pnpm install --frozen-lockfile` fails at node-llama-cpp postinstall. Core dependencies (vitest, tsx) are functional. No live Telegram bot API for end-to-end testing with real photo delivery.\n\n### Risk checklist\n\n- Did user-visible behavior change? **Yes** — groups with `ingest: true` now receive media-bearing messages via hooks instead of skipping them. Groups without `ingest` are unchanged.\n- Did config, environment, or migration behavior change? **No** — uses existing `ingest` config field, no new config needed.\n- Did security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? **No**\n- Highest-risk area: The `resolveChannelGroupPolicy` call adds a small overhead per unaddressed media message. Mitigation: only called when `mentionDecision.shouldSkip` is true (the existing skip path), not for every message.\n- Risk mitigation: Minimal additive change — only adds a config check before an existing `return true`. Default behavior (no ingest) is completely unchanged. Resolution hierarchy matches the established text-message pattern.\n",
        "branch": "fix/92067-telegram-ingest-media",
